he birth or adoption of a child. While most policies are designed to help women return to work, this is only half of the puzzle. The second half requires men to be meaningful partners by encouraging them to take equal time at home.Ultimately, Kaufman arrives at a rational solution that will promote gender equity through a policy that enables parents at companies of all sizes to spend six months with their new child.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFamilies. 0aParental leave. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  aBreastfeeding.  aChildren’s health.  aDaddy "a.  aEmployer policies.  aEqual parenting.  aFamily and Medical Leave Act.  aFathers and caregiving.  aGay couples.  aGender equality.  aGendered policies.  aMaternal bonding.  aMaternal employment.  aMaternity leave.  aMen’s earnings.  aPaternity leave.  aPay gap.  aPostpartum depression.  aSecondary parents.  aShared parental leave.  aSocial policy.  aUnequal pay.  aWomen’s career advancement.  aWomen’s health.  aWorkplace context.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831107227030 cprintz978147981036940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479820146.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479820146423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479820146/original  a978-